Variable: Notes
Notes: Using online food tracking apps to observe food patterns and total caloric intake in proteins vs carbs vs fats may be a useful tool for modifying certain dietary habits if needed (Chronometer, myfitnesspal, etc)

Variable: For workouts lasting greater than or equal to 90 minutes, high carbohydrate (2-3g/kg body weight), moderate protein, low-fat meal, 300-500 kcals, ~2hours before activity is consumed. Fat and fiber intake is kept low to prevent stomach discomfort.
Notes:
Here are some examples of additional foods that contain healthy fats that you can incorporate into your diet for your days prior to your long runs or races:
- vegetable oils, such as olive oil, sesame oil, and canola oil
- nuts, including almonds, pecans, and cashews
- avocado
- peanut butter and almond butter
- seeds, such as sunflower, pumpkin, and sesame
- full fat yogurt
- tofu


Small snacks prior to exercising include pb&j or granola bars or sports drinks (30-45 minutes prior). Higher carb content snacks/meals (pastas, breads, rice, etc) may be consumed at least one and half to two hours prior to exercising (in addition to proper hydration)
Fruits are also a good option as you get additional sources of carbs and sugars for your workout

Variable: Drink 400-600ml (14-22oz) before workout for optimal hydration
Notes:
Hydration prior to exercise:
2 hours prior: 2-3 cups
30 minutes prior: 1 cup
For every 30 minutes exercising: 0.5 to 1 cup
Continue to drink water throughout the day (before and after)!!
If a coffee drinker, add an additional cup or two prior to exercising and after
DO NOT CHUG! Give yourself ample time to drink and gradually drink fluids.

Remember to focus more on hydration prior to your morning runs as well (or when you eat more gels) as sleeping and depending on what you had the night prior, may add on to what you may be lacking in regards to your nutrition for your run

Using online food tracking apps to observe food patterns and total caloric intake in proteins vs carbs vs fats may be a useful tool for modifying certain dietary habits if needed and trying to gain weight (Chronometer, myfitnesspal, etc)

Do not make any major changes mid-season! As a high school athlete, it is important to slowly incorporate changes, such as diet, to you routine especially if you are trying to add weight. The biggest benefit for you will be increasing your protein and potentially fat intake over time. Protein will be crucial while increasing resistance exercise and building the strength to better endure higher mileage and intensities (mainly started in the off-season). Healthy fats will aid in the weight gain and allow your body additional sources of energy if need be with the longer workouts. Carb intake should remain high as well - a good way to keep this high is incorporating more fruits and vegetables into your diet.

DO NOT CHUG! Give yourself ample time to drink and gradually drink fluids.

Focus mainly on proteins, fruits and vegetables and add starchy veggies and grains around your training sessions to support the exercise. Limit added fat to 1-2TBSP per meal. 
Also think about your hunger scale and aim to hang out betweem 2 and 7, (10 being super full and 1 being super hungry). Your goal is to be hungry at meals and snacks!

Notes: You are looking to improve on body composition. A lot can be done with diet. The first thing we want to normalize is your protein intake. Eat breakfast if you are hungry. You could have a Greek yogurt with some fruits and nuts. At lunch aim for a big salad with a protein portion the size of your hand. You can add bread if you are exercising more during the day. For snacks think about adding more proteins too: Greek yogurt, jerky, nuts, Rise bar. For better recovery also think about adding more proteins with a fruit for example. If you are exercising more than 90 min, you will need to start eating during your run. Think about small bites of food, Clif bloks are a good choice or you could have bites of bars every 15-20 minutes. Sports nutrition drinks also work as long as it is not too hot. If the weather is warm the tendency is to drink more liquid which could also lead to ingestion of more carbohydrates and gastro-intestinal distress.

Notes:
You are interested in improving body composition and weight loss. You are doing a good job at incorporating proteins at lunch and dinner but you should think about increasing protein intake also at breakfast and for your snacks. For example, you could add some protein powder to your cashew yogurt (Vega or whey isolate). Same thing with your snacks. In the evening instead of snacking on cookies, have a glass of soy milk or almond milk with some protein powder too to help with satiety. 
Add back more carbohydrates to your lunch and dinner when you are exercising more during the day.
Since you don't get a lot of dairy, look for milks that are fortified in calcium. Green leafy veggies, brocoli, tofu, almonds, seeds are also rich in calcium. 
You are also taking a 2000iu vitamin D supplements. Think about getting re-tested to see where you are since this is a higher dose.

Vitamin B12 should get re-tested too. You can alternate days where you take a vitamin and when you are not. Meats, fish and eggs are rich in vitamin B12 so you should have already plenty from your diet.

Weight Loss
Notes:
For weight loss, I would still get a composition test done to monitor how your body comp. changes while you are trying to lose weight as a whole. I do agree with your previous dietitians in the sense that the body typically has a set weight that it likes to hover around. It sounded like you are active and eat fairly healthy, and your downfalls were eating too much at once (you had mentioned eating a whole bag of nuts at once). 

With weight loss goals in combination with your increasing age and the wight that your body has settled at, small changes to your diet will reap minor changes towards your goals. If you want to see a more drastic change while still being safe and staying healthy, you have to tighten up the laces on your diet and avoid excessive eating (beyond what you need to perform and stay healthy). The best way to do this is to test your resting metabolic rate and get an idea of what your body needs. Without this, you may currently be restricting below what your needs are and that may then, not only encourage slowing of your metabolism, but may also encourage fat storage.

Notes: To improve on body composition, you want to have the size of your hand in protein at each meal. You can add a little bit of fat (avoid vegetable oils, olive oil is great!). The other half of your plate should be fruits and vegetables. Add more starches if you want but not more than the size of your fist or a slice of bread. Examples for breakfast: 2-3 eggs with fruits and a slice of bread, oatmeal with greek yogurt with fruits. You will have better blood sugar control that way and perhaps this will normalize your apetite. You should still listen to your appetite and aim to be at 8/10 after a meal, no more. Improving body comosition starts with diet and not exercise. If you run 2 miles you are burning 200 kcal only!

Notes:
Vitamin D also helps the absorption of calcium! I have included a few fish and animal product sources if you are not completely plantbased.

Foods that provide vitamin D include:
	Fatty fish like tuna, mackerel, and salmon
	Foods fortified with vitamin D, like some dairy products, orange juice, soy milk, and cereals
	Cheese and eggs (if you are not fully pant based)

Foods that are high in calcium:
	Spinach (be sure to consume with an acid such as a spritz of lemon)
	Kale (be sure to consume with an acid such as a sprits of lemon)
	Okra
	Collards
	Soybeans
	White beans
	Some fish, like sardines, salmon, perch, and rainbow trout
	Foods that are calcium-fortified, such as some orange juice, oatmeal, and breakfast cereal.

I would recommend a product like UCAN superstarch (Sports Basement or website) Have one packet before, it will release very slowly and let your muscle use it without the need to use insulin.

Variable: Drinks 450-675ml(16-24oz) for every lb of body weight lost
Calcium and Vitamin D
GI Issues
Weight Loss
Notes: On days where you don't exercise you can rely on a good source of protein and fruits and vegetables. You don't need to eat denser carb, that will lower your need for insulin and let your body stay in fat burning mode. I would avoid beans and legumes on those days because they have a bit more of carbohydrates even though pretty low glycemic. You can have a little bit of fat (2 thumbs). A protein powder would be a good choice. Try to limit your fruit intake to 2 per day. Check your blood sugar throughout the day if/when you make those changes. On days when you exercise you can add back more dense carbohydrates and beans (1/2 cup to 3/4 cup) preferably after your exercise session when your body is going to be receptive to it and won't drive your insulin need.

Focusing on your primary goal (weight loss or maintaining a healthy weight), follow these guidelines given for grams/hr and only do so if you have been training for an hr or more. If you are not experiencing GI distress, you still run the risk of weight gain if you are consuming more than you need.  Also, please note that if you are walking, walk jogging, or biking at lower intensities for an hour, the need for refusing is not as great as if you were running or working at higher intensities.  As we discussed, for your goal of bone health, it sounds like you are taking the right supplements (those that your doctor prescribed), to help you maintain your bone density as best you can. By the end of the week I will email you a few exercises that may help slow the progression of bone loss as well as a few balance exercises and core exercises, as these seemed to be of interest to you. Also, below is a list of food sources of some of the nutrients that you were interested in.

CoQ10: walnuts, peanuts, soybeans, spinach, azuki beans, wheat germ and whole grains. A 1/2-cup serving of boiled, chopped broccoli contains 0.5 milligrams. Eating these foods raw (if you can do so without stomach irritation) provides the greatest amounts of coenzyme Q10, as heating changes the qualities of the enzyme.

Omega 3 FA: You seem to be getting a good amount of this from the fish that you are eating. Ground, refrigerated flaxseeds can also help you get the Omega 3 FAs that you need!

Here are few other little tidbits that you may or may not find helpful, as you selected 'Weight Loss" as one of your goals on the website.  When it comes to food, our relationship can be incredibly complicated. Here are a few reminders to help keep maintain your healthy relationship with food. 

1.	Environment- Keep the areas that you are in the most (work, home), clear of refined, processed foods  (out of sight, out of mind) while surrounding yourself with the foods that you need and that are healthy.
2.	Every meal doesnt have to be a process or event. Many cultures and relationships center around food, but not every meal needs to. Sometimes you just need to eat to fuel the machine. 
3.	If you tend to miss meals (especially those after your workouts), you are missing out on a window of opportunity to optimize gains. You already did the hard part! Now do yourself a favor and be sure to refuel, rehydrate, and sleep well!

Notes:
It was great meeting you Tuesday Kathy! I first wanted to address your overall health and bone density goals. Along with working with your doctor to monitor your bone density and vitamin and mineral levels, we also discussed the importance of supplementing your running with resistance training to help maintain or potentially improve your bone density. The band work that you are doing is great, however it may be advantageous to start adding some free weights to your routine. You would want to start off slow and work your way up to heavier weight (5, 8, 10 lbs) over a number of months. The weight used should be dictated by your ability to perform the exercises with proper form*, it should feel challenging for the last few repetitions but do-able, and lastly, you should not have any pain unrelated to the expected temporary gradual burn or sensation you feel during resistance training.  

The American College of Sports Medicine recommends resistance type training a minimum of 2-3 days per week targeting your major muscle groups (chest, back, core, legs) to challenge your strength using 2-4 sets of 10-15 repetitions (at a weight that feels challenging) with ~1-2 mins rest between sets. This would be a good start for someone who is already doing band training and resistance work. I would also add the gentle lateral hops, balance, and forward and backward hopping that we talked about to help maintain your bone health. Remember the goal with bone density is to maintain, and that maintenance takes doing exercises that potentially contribute to bone generation and/or maintenance, on a regular basis through your life, not just one and done. This in conjunction with the appropriate nutrient in your diet will give you the best chance at maintaining and possibly improving health.

Weight Loss
Notes:
Aside from the general recommendations for weight loss, be sure that you have access to snacks during the day. I understand that food and fluids can be challenging because you are in a lab most of your day, but if you tend to wait as long as possible before eating, over time, your metabolism will slow which lends to increased fat storage. There is also risk of  potential muscle loss more so than if you were eating more frequently. Also, as you have experienced, you may then have a tendency to overeat when waiting so long to eat, which will also not help with weight loss.  

As far as snacks go, below are a few suggestions to get your creative snacking brain going:)

- Jicama and hummus
- Grapes and walnuts
- Raisins, nuts, and Roasted Broad Beans (by Enlightened Foods)
- Healthy food bar (try to have real food, but always have a bar available for emergencies).

Notes: The average person only requires about 0.8-1.0 grams of protein per kg of body weight. The amount of protein may increase with strenuous exercise or training for an endurance event. Since you are working out leisurely, aim to eat around 65-80 grams of protein per day, which is easy to do especially if you are eating  few servings of meat per day. 1 oz of meat contains about 7 grams protein, and 3 oz (or the size of your palm without fingers) is a typical meat serving and contains about 21 grams of protein.

Variable: Consistently Inadequate Carbohydrate
Consistently Inadequate Protein Intake
Notes:
Your daily protein needs are about 80-100 grams per day for your current level of exercise. 
Your body uses protein to build and repair tissues, make enzymes, hormones, transport nutrients, make muscle contract, regulate water balance etc. It is important to remember that the body can use protein as an energy source, but it is not a preferred type of fuel and is used in very small amounts for this purpose.  For example, 3 ounces of lean meat provide ~30grams of protein, 8oz of milk has 8 grams and a slice of bread has 2 grams. Good sources or protein are nuts, seed, beans, low-fat dairy, meat, fish, tofu, eggs. Make sure that you have a good source of protein at each meal and snack.

Notes:
You daily protein goal is 70-80 grams per day. During the lacrosse season, focus more on getting toward 80 grams per day. If you want to do a spot check on your calorie and protein intake, use the myfitnesspal app. 

Your body uses protein to build and repair tissues, make enzymes, hormones, transport nutrients, make muscle contract, regulate water balance etc. It is important to remember that the body can use protein as an energy source, but it is not a preferred type of fuel and is used in very small amounts for this purpose. Endurance athletes require 1.2-1.6 g / kg of body weight. For example, 3 ounces of lean meat provide ~30grams of protein, 8oz of milk has 8 grams and a slice of bread has 2 grams. Good sources or protein are nuts, seed, beans, low-fat dairy, meat, fish, tofu, eggs. Make sure that you have a good source of protein at each meal and snack.

Variable: Consistently Inadequate Carbohydrate
Consistently Inadequate Protein Intake
Notes:
Your body uses protein to build and repair tissues, make enzymes, hormones, transport nutrients, make muscle contract, regulate water balance etc. It is important to remember that the body can use protein as an energy source, but it is not a preferred type of fuel and is used in very small amounts for this purpose. Endurance athletes require 1.2-1.6 g / kg of body weight. For example, 3 ounces of lean meat provide ~30grams of protein, 8oz of milk has 8 grams and a slice of bread has 2 grams. Good sources or protein are nuts, seed, beans, low-fat dairy, meat, fish, tofu, eggs. Make sure that you have a good source of protein at each meal and snack.

Vegetarians need to be more cognizant of their protein intake. For your current weight and when you get into marathon training you need about 62 to 72 grams of protein per day. If you're not exercising you only need 52 grams per day

Notes:
Your body uses protein to build and repair tissues, make enzymes, hormones, transport nutrients, make muscle contract, regulate water balance etc. It is important to remember that the body can use protein as an energy source, but it is not a preferred type of fuel and is used in very small amounts for this purpose. Endurance athletes require 1.2-1.6 g / kg of body weight. For example, 3 ounces of lean meat provide ~30grams of protein, 8oz of milk has 8 grams and a slice of bread has 2 grams. Good sources or protein are nuts, seed, beans, low-fat dairy, meat, fish, tofu, eggs. Make sure that you have a good source of protein at each meal and snack. 

Your daily protein goal for your current level of training is 53-64 grams of protein per day. When you get closer to the half marathon, aim closer to 64 grams.

Notes: Cutting 500 calories/day should lead to 1 lb of weight loss per week.
